attachments.title: Obana (尾花) – Minami Senju, Tokyo
attachments.text:
Unagi (&#12358;&#12394;&#12366;), or freshwater eel is one of the most popular Japanese ingredients despite of it&rsquo;s expensive price. Usually to be served Unagi is grilled, but there are two way to grill it with or without sauce.
Unagi grilled with sauce is called kabayaki (&#33970;&#28988;), Japanese people usually eat it as a side dish for their drinks or put it over&nbsp;rice and served is as main course which usually called Unadon (&#12358;&#12394;&#20028;) or Unajyuu (&#12358;&#12394;&#37325;).
The second one is called shirayaki (&#30333;&#28988;) that means white grill, as the name would suggest, shirayaki is grilled&nbsp;without sauce and usually it served as an appetizer because the taste is lighter than the kabayaki.
If you have a chance to come to Tokyo and you want to eat Unagi, Obana (&#23614;&#33457;) is the place to go. Obana has been open since Meiji era (1868~1912) and until now it&rsquo;s still well known as one of the best Unagi restaurant in Tokyo (the best in my opinion). I was introduced to Obana by my father-in-law who went to Obana for first time about 40 years ago and been there multiple time since that.
I recommend you to order Shirayaki&nbsp;(4500&nbsp;yen)

Unajyuu (small 4500 yen, large 5500 yen)

I also recommend Kimosui (&#32925;&#21560;&#12356;) which is Unagi liver soup (400 yen) as a side dish for your Unajyuu.
What makes Obana&rsquo;s Unagi so special compared to other unagi shop are their grilling technique. Not like other Unagi shop Obana&rsquo;s Unagi doesn&rsquo;t have many burned spot (almost none in my case) and it&nbsp;so soft, it just melts in my mouth!
Shop Info :
Name : Obana (&#23614;&#33457;)
Address : Tokyo-to Arakawa-ku Minami Senju 5-33-1 (Google Maps)
Phone Number : 03-3801-4670
